is sometimes also a translation of <b>Breathnach</b> ‘Briton’.","English: in Yorkshire and Lancashire the name is sometimes a shortened form of   Walshaw  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walshe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eoin, Murph.","English and Irish: variant of   Walsh  ."]},{"name":"McBratney","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Breatnaigh</b> ‘son of the Briton’ (referring to the Welsh of Strathclyde). Compare   Walsh   and   Galbraith  ."]},{"name":"Welsh","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>welshe</i> (Old English <i>wēalisc</i>, <i>wēlisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’, for someone from Wales or a speaker of the Welsh language. Compare   Walsh   and   Wallace  .","Americanized form of German   Welsch  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian and Jewish (from Ukraine)   Voloshin   or its Polish variant <b>Wołoszyn</b> (see   Woloszyn  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":19,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":28,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":63,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":94,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Walsh was born as the son of William le Walsh and Alice La Zouche. He had at least 1 son with Isabal Elizabeth de Kykenho. He died from 1307 to 1314, in Wanlip, Leicestershire, England."},"et":{"–from 1307 to 1314":"–1307 kuni 1314","1280–1311":"1280–1311","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","–1314":"–1314","1270–1345":"1270–1345","–1350":"–1350","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1223–1256":"1223–1256","1350":"1350","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Abt 1285":"umbes 1285","from 1307 to 1314":"1307 kuni 1314","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1314":"1314","1225":"1225","1